body:
Although there might be some perf issues to be ironed out, based on the sample code you shared above, the perf comparison between Torch and ORT is not apple-to-apple.

The Torch inputs (and possibly outputs too ? - don't know where the contents of `torch_outputs` exist) seem to be copied over to the device (and outputs from the device to cpu ?) outside the latency measurement.
Input: `x = x.to(device=device)` copies it over to the device before model evaluation.

With ORT, the CPU input is copied over to the device and the outputs are numpy arrays (underlying memory copied over from CUDA to CPU) and these operations are included as part of the latency measurement.

Take a look at IOBinding to bind CUDA memory as inputs/outputs to ORT and this should atleast help get an apple-to-apple comparison and see the "real" delta between PyTorch and ORT - https://www.onnxruntime.ai/python/api_summary.html#id2

Thank you for your response @hariharans29.
You were right. The comparison wasn't correct.
I changed the code and it looks like it's all right now (hope so), but performance didn't change much.

Now inputs and outputs for PyTorch and for ORT stored on GPU
For ORT I use [scenario 3 with IOBinding](https://www.onnxruntime.ai/python/api_summary.html#id2)
Also, I'm binding inputs and outputs before for loop.

GPU results:

> Device cuda:0
> Batch size 16
> Batch amount 100
> 100 model_torch(x) took 12.3291300
> 100 ort_session.run took 61.0712226

In order not to spam with copy-paste, I attach files with code ([code.txt](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/6727506/code.txt)) and output ([output.txt](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/6727531/output.txt))

Also, I tried to use GraphOptimization with SessionOptions like it was suggested [there](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2796#issuecomment-574289547).
I end up with a bit better results (100 ort_session.run took 60.8482985), but still way slower than PyTorch.

Thanks for sharing the updated code. The IOBinding part looks correct. It is strange that the perf is exactly the same as before. I didn't expect the entire problem to go away with IOBinding but still expected that doing the device data transfer outside the measurement made the perf less worse.

We will have to investigate.

Could you please directly share the exported ONNX model (We  wouldn't have to setup Torch and do the export ourselves then) ?

Is it possible to share the perf numbers with a batch size of 1 ?

Also, if you could enable verbose logging, and upload the logs that would be a bonus too.

It looks strange to me too. I think I have some fundamental mistake somewhere.

GPU Results with bs=1:

> Device cuda:0
> Batch size 1
> Batch amount 100
> 100 model_torch(x) took 1.8733530
> 100 ort_session.run took 7.9171801

The only thing about the logging I found was [RunOptions](https://www.onnxruntime.ai/python/api_summary.html?highlight=verbose#onnxruntime.RunOptions). Please correct me if I turned on logging in the wrong way.
I uploaded updated code, full output for bs=1 and *.onnx model to [google drive](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1gTFM9D0kgM0awl9moJSxJacgOz6715g9?usp=sharing)

@tianleiwu thank you, I tried your code with different batch sizes on my machine. It's better but still worse than PyTorch inference.

GPU Results with bs=1:

> Device cuda:0
> Batch size 1
> Batch amount 100
> 100 ort_session.run took 4.1152403

GPU Results with bs=16:

> Device cuda:0
> Batch size 16
> Batch amount 100
> 100 ort_session.run took 57.0434766

An interesting thing: I did similar (correct time measurement with IOBinding scenario 3, warm up, extended optimization level) to [an example from PyTorch Docs](https://pytorch.org/tutorials/advanced/super_resolution_with_onnxruntime.html) (where PyTorch was faster for me too) and get nearly the same results on GPU for Pytorch and ORT (ORT ~5% faster).
So, maybe this is due to the "unfortunate" combination of hardware and network architecture?

It could be that certain Torch CUDA op implementations are faster than ORT's CUDA implementations for this architecture. We will have to profile it. I haven't looked at the model yet, but does the model have a lot of Pad nodes by any chance ? I think our Pad implementation could potentially need some perf enhancements.

Ok. I turned `verbose=True` during `torch.onnx.export` and according to its output I think that my model (efficientnet-b5 from [smp](https://github.com/qubvel/segmentation_models.pytorch)) has ~240 pad nodes
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30793581/124941173-e6b74f80-e00a-11eb-8d23-7fa408c9b56e.png)
Will take a look at this next week

issue.title: Improve performance of Pad CUDA kernel

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 

Most image models use the `Pad` operation to pad only along the `height` and `width` dimensions (i.e.) they convert tensors of shape [N, C, H, W] to [N, C, H + pad_h, W +pad_w]. Our current implementation for Pad in CUDA is too "generic" (processes N-D tensors accounting for possible padding in all dims) to optimally process this often-occurring use-case. This change adds logic to recognize this special case and adds a specialized implementation (Torch-inspired) for the same.

This change closes the gap with Torch for model in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8166. These gains should be applicable to all image models using such padding patterns.

The existing unit tests for Pad are very exhaustive and there are a good number of tests using the new specialized code path. No new unit tests required for this change. 

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8166
Possibly provides good gains for models in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8362 and https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7681 (they are encouraged to try with this commit)

body: Hi @snazau - Please try with the referenced PR. It (together with proper warm-up, IOBinding, and highest graph optimization) should close the gap with Torch. Please re-open if you have more questions.
